<br>
I would agree that backing your pet off 1 second prior to the spell landing seems to work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/utrezark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trezark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(5/8/01 4:26:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22.topic&index=7>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: PVP Pet Poofing...</span><hr size=1> I dunno if this has anything to do with the poofing problem here, but I've been told that in a PvP situation, if you do anything at all to aggro your pet (i.e. somehow manage to make it on to your pet's hate list), it will kill itself.  I've experimented with this myself, and I seem to recall casting a DD on my pet once in an arena and having him die.<br>
<br>
Now I'm not entirely sure if dispelling a target that your pet is attacking is grounds for it to get annoyed at you, but I suppose it's a possibility.  Maybe the pet sees the cancel as a benevolent spell and thus gets mad at you for helping its target?  I don't see how, since casting cancel on a mob will aggro it, but maybe these things are more complicated than they seem... <p><BR><CENTER><hr size=1 WIDTH=75%>
<font face=arial size=-2>[45 Magician] <A HREF="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=57050">Trezark S`Dious</A> (Dark Elf) &lt;<A HREF="http://www.black-reign.net">Black Reign</A>&gt; SERVER: Vazaelle<BR><i>"You could no more evade my wrath than you could your own shadow..."</i></FONT></CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ularanos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Laranos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(5/13/01 10:54:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: PVP Pet Poofing...</span><hr size=1> Ok, here's the skinny. Instead of dealing with rogue pets, VI coded it so that -anything- that would make your pet go rogue poofs the pet. In the arena this means if you hit it with a bolt...if you annull a target with an empty buff slot, it goes rogue, and poofs. If a bard charms it and lets it go, it poofs, etc. etc. etc. I have done a -lot- of experimenting with this stuff. Basically, rather then just -fix- the problems associated with pets going rogue, they decided to make pets poof into non-existance instead. Basically, that means we are unable to use an entire spell line in pvp because it might poof our pet, bards get a free manaless kill on our pets, and enchanters basically get to screw us. Absor was once quoted as saying that a mage's pet is 50% of their power...well, for pvp, eliminating that 50% is as easy as shooting fish in a barrel.<br>
